DefinitionsImage Measure of $\mu$ by $f$: Let $(X_1,\Sigma_1)$ and $(X_2,\Sigma_2)$ be two measurable spaces, and $f : X_1	o X_2$ a $\Sigma_1 ackslash\Sigma_2$-measurable function. For any measure $\mu$ on $\Sigma_1$, the map $\mu_f : \Sigma_2 	o [0, \infty]$, defined by $$\mu_f(S):=\mu(f^{-1}(S))$$ is called the image measure of $\mu$ by $f$. Distribution: Let $Y$ be a metric space. For any $Y $-valued random variable $x$ on a probability space $(X,\Sigma,\mathbf{p})$, the image measure of $\mu$ by $x$ (where we think of $x$ as $\Sigma ackslash \mathcal{B}(Y )$-measurable) is called the distribution of $x$ that is, $\mathbf {p}_x$ is the Borel measure on $Y$ such that $$\mathbf{p}_x(S):=\mathbf{p}(x^{-1}(S))\ \ \mbox{ for each }\ S\in\mathcal{B}(Y)$$ For the single measure on the probability space $(X,\Sigma,\mathbf{p})$, if we have different random variables, we will have different distributions. For any metric space $Y$, the distribution $\mathbf{p}_x$ of a $Y$-valued random variable $x$ on a probability space $(X,\Sigma,\mathbf{p})$ describes the probabilities for every event that may involve $x$. Distribution Function: When $x$ is a random variable that is, $Y = \mathbb{R} $, the distribution function induced by $\mathbf {p}_x $is called the distribution function of $x$. We denote this distribution function by $F_x$, and say that $x$ is continuous if $F_x$ is a continuous function. On the other hand, we say that $x$ is discrete if $F_x$ is a discrete distribution function. We often describe the probabilistic behavior of a random variable by specifying its distribution function directly. So, the statement$$x \mbox{ is a random variable on }X \mbox{ with the distribution function }F$$means that $x$ is a random variable on some probability space $(X,\Sigma,\mathbf{p})$ such that the distribution of $x$ is the Lebesgue-Stieltjes probability measure induced by $F$, that is, $F = F_x$. For the single measure on the probability space $(X,\Sigma,\mathbf{p})$, if we have different random variables, we will also have different distribution functions. Equal $\mu$-almost everywhere, Equal almost surely: Let $Y$ be a separable metric space, and $x$ and $y$ two $Y $-valued random variables on a measure space $(X,\Sigma,\mu)$. If $\mu{x
