mathbf{p}(a, b]$$for any $-\infty \leq a \leq b &lt; 1$$$\ell_x(a,\infty) = 1 - F (a) = \mathbf{p}(a,\infty)$$for any $-\infty\leq  a$. Thus $\ell_x$ and $\mathbf{p}$ agree on the semialgebra of all right-semiclosed intervals. If $F$ is not invertible, need to define Pseudo-Inverse: Define the pseudo-inverse of a distribution function $F$ as the map $F^{-1} :(0,1)	o \mathbb{R} $ with$$F^{-1}(\omega) := \inf {t\in \mathbb{R} : F(t) \geq\omega}.$$ Example 2.3: Consider the probability space $(\mathbb{N},2^\mathbb{N},\mathbf{p})$ where $\mathbf{p}{i} = 2^{-i}$ for each $i\in \mathbb{N}$. Any two ($Y$-valued) random variables $x$ and $y$ on this space is almost surely equal to each other is $x = y$. Example 2.3: Consider the probability space $([0,1], \mathcal{B}[0, 1], \ell)$ and take any two random variables $x$ and $y$ on this space. If $x|{[0,1]\setminus\mathbb{Q} }= y|{[0,1]\setminus\mathbb{Q}}$, then $x =_{a.s.} y$. Of course, we can replace $\mathbb{Q}$ with any countable subset of $[0, 1]$ in this observation. Example 2.4: Consider the probability space $([0,1], \mathcal{B}[0, 1], \ell)$. Consider the sequence $(x_m) $ in $\mathbb{R}^{[0,1]}$ where $x_m(\omega) := 1 + \omega^m$. Then, $x_m	o 1$ is false, because $x_m(1) = 2$ for each $m$, and yet ${x_m	o 1} = [0, 1)$, and hence $x_m 	o_{a.s.} 1$. Example 2.4: Consider the probability space $([0,1], \mathcal{B}[0, 1], \ell)$. Consider the sequence $(y_m)$ in $\mathbb{R}^{[0,1]}$ where $y_m$ is the indicator function of $[0,  rac{m+1}{2m}]$ on $[0,1]$. Then, $y_m	o_{a.s}. \mathbf{1}_{[0, rac{1}{2})}$, but $y_m( rac{1}{2}) = 1$ for each $m$. Reference Efe A. Ok, “Measure and Probability Theory with Economic Applications”; Lecture notes, ECON 30400 2, Autumn 2020, Introduction: Mathematical Methods In Economics; Walter Rudin, 1987, “Real and Complex Analysis”; Walter Rudin, 1976, “Principle of Mathematical Analysis”;
